pulfalight.title: Collection-level content warning scope note should inherit down

comments.body: https://github.com/pulibrary/pulfalight/tree/1237-content-warning-scope makes scopecontent inherit down (and fixes inheritance for all the notes we defined.) I'm blocked on the content warning special behavior portion of this ticket until I have an example where a parent has a content warning a component has a scopecontent but no content warning. @faithc @ccleeton ?

> We want to treat scopecontent notes with the Content Warning header as special for the purpose of inheritance. Content warnings inherit down always.
> 
> Lower levels can have their own content warnings, but can't remove a parent's content warning.

I'm not sure this is true; what you mean by "Lower levels can have their own content warnings, but can't remove a parent's content warning." A warning at a lower level should supersede a parent warning. For example, there could be a collection-level warning noting the existence of harmful content and a note at a lower level with explicit information about particular materials, if that makes sense. For example, the collection-level warning for TC040 is superseded by the note at [TC040_c00001](https://findingaids.princeton.edu/catalog/TC040_c00001).

@faithc What we had talked about was if a TC040 had a "Content Warning", and TC040_c00001 had a "Scope & Contents" note, then TC040_c00001 should have a "Scope & Contents" as well as a "Content Warning", and there's no way to make it so it doesn't.

I'm also hearing we can't find an example where the parent has a content warning and the child has a scope & content w/ no content warning, though.

Ok, right, yes. 

And I can't think of an example off the top of my head where this is true.

We talked about this more:

`scopecontent` should NOT inherit down, but `scopecontent` notes with the `Content Warning` header should.
